'''Gary Cziko''' is an American researcher, and author<ref name="UIUC faculty page" /> in the field of [[educational psychology]] at the [[University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign]] who has worked on the philosophical model known as [[perceptual control theory]] (PCT) – a model whose original developer, [[William T. Powers]], was his mentor.<ref name=Deacon>{{cite journal |last=Deacon |first=Terrence |date=2001|volume=89|issue=1 |title=Circling Back to an Organism-Centered Behavioral Biology |url=http://www.americanscientist.org/bookshelf/pub/circling-back-to-an-organism-centered-behavioral-biology |journal= [[American Scientist]]}}</ref> He has written two introductory books on the subject, and in 1995 he introduced the concept of  "universal selectionism" into the PCT model.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Gontier |first=Nathalie |date=2002 |title=Evolutionary Epistemology |url=http://www.iep.utm.edu/evo-epis/ |journal= [[Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy]] |publisher=[[University of Tennessee at Martin]] |access-date=May 6, 2016}}</ref>

== Education and career ==

Cziko received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in psychology from [[Queens College, City University of New York]], a [[Master of Arts]] degree in psychology from [[McGill University]]  in [[Montreal|Montreal, Quebec]], Canada, in 1975, and a [[Doctor of Philosophy]] (Ph.D.) from McGill University in 1978.<ref name="UIUC faculty page">{{cite web |url=https://education.illinois.edu/faculty/g-cziko |title=Gary Cziko |website=Faculty profile page at [[University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign]]}}</ref>
He was a [[post-doctoral]] research fellow for the [[Quebec Ministry of Education]] at the [[University of Montreal]] during 1978–79.<ref name="UIUC faculty page" /> Since 1979, Cziko has been on the faculty of the University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign. He became an associate professor in 1986 and a full professor in 1998.

== Selected publications ==
In 1989, Cziko published one of his first academic papers relating to PCT:
*{{cite journal |last=Cziko |first=Gary |date=1989 |title=Unpredictability and Indeterminism in Human Behavior: Arguments and Implications for  |url=http://www.sscnet.ucla.edu/polisci/faculty/chwe/austen/cziko.pdf |journal=[[Educational Researcher]]|volume=18|issue=3|doi=10.3102/0013189X018003017|pages=17–25}}
He has also authored two introductions to PCT, both published by [[MIT Press]]:
*{{cite book |last=Cziko |first=Gary |date=1995 |title=Without Miracles: Universal Selection Theory and the Second Darwinian Revolution |lccn=95000943 |publisher=[[MIT Press]] |page= |isbn=0-262-03232-5}}<ref>{{cite journal|first=Michael|last=Bradie|department=Book Reviews|title=Without miracles: universal selection theory and the second Darwinian revolution|journal=Philosophical Psychology|volume=10|pages=399–401|year=1997|issue=3|doi=10.1080/09515089708573229}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Review of Gary Cziko, Without Miracles: Universal Selection Theory and the Second Darwinian Revolution|first=Dawn|last=Ogden|journal=[[Philosophy in Review]]|volume=17|issue=3|pages=160–162|year=1997|url=https://journals.uvic.ca/index.php/pir/issue/view/425}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|first=Stanley N.|last=Salthe|title=Without Miracles: Universal Selection Theory and the Second Darwinian Revolution. Gary Cziko|department=New Biological Books: Reviews and Brief Notices|journal=[[The Quarterly Review of Biology]]|volume=72|issue=2|year=1996|page=275|doi=10.1086/419392}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Seeing everything through Darwin's eyes (review of Without Miracles)|journal=[[BioScience]]|department=Books|year=1996|volume=46|issue=11|pages=872–873|doi=10.2307/1312973|first=Arthur M.|last=Shapiro|authorlink=Arthur Shapiro (ecologist)}}</ref>
*{{cite book |last=Cziko |first=Gary |date=2000 |title=The Things We Do : Using The Lessons of Bernard and Darwin to Understand The What, How, and Why of Our Behavior |lccn=99051843 |publisher=[[MIT Press]] |page= |isbn=0-262-03277-5}}<ref name=Deacon /><ref>{{cite journal|first=Niall|last=Shanks|authorlink=Niall Shanks|title=The Things We Do : Using The Lessons of Bernard and Darwin to Understand The What, How, and Why of Our Behavior|department=Book Reviews|journal=Philosophical Psychology|volume=17|pages=2|year=2004|doi=10.1080/0951508042000239093}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|first=Dean Keith|last=Simonton|authorlink=Dean Simonton|title=The Things We Do: Using the Lessons of Bernard and Darwin to Understand the What, How, and Why of Our Behavior. Gary Cziko|department=New Biological Books: Reviews and Brief Notices|journal=[[The Quarterly Review of Biology]]|volume=76|issue=2|year=2001|page=268|doi=10.1086/393971}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|first=Serge|last=Larivière|title=The Things We Do: Using the Lessons of Bernard and Darwin to Understand the What, How and Why of Our Behaviour|department=Book Reviews|journal=[[Journal of Mammalogy]]|volume=82|issue=3|year=2001|pages=882–883|doi=10.1644/1545-1542(2001)082<0883:>2.0.CO;2}}</ref>

== Awards and recognitions ==

In 2008, Cziko was a [[Fulbright Program|Fulbright Scholar]] in Chile.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ten at U. of I. awarded Fulbright Scholar Grants|date=December 6, 2007|first=Laura|last=Prusik|url=https://news.illinois.edu/blog/view/6367/206455|publisher=Illinois News Bureau, University of Illinois}}</ref>

